<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 2 SPEED REAR AXLES: SPICER - ASSEMBLE - PINION</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="8">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>General</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Assemble the proper slinger and inner bearing cone onto pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401522">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401522" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1401522" filename="../figg14/G1401522.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="514px" scalefitheight="352px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 22. Pinion Gear Assembly</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press roller bearing on the drive pinion (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401523">Figure 23</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401523" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1401523" filename="../figg14/G1401523.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 23. Roller Bearing Reassembly</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Stake roller bearing in six places, using staking tool (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401523">Figure 23</hotlnk>). Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s14015_39.xml" xrefid="hl1401501">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>, for staking tool
                    information.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Make sure all carrier bores are free from all nicks, dirt, or any other contamination.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the outer pinion bearing cup into the carrier.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the inner pinion bearing cup into the carrier.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge or shim stock to ensure bearing cups are completely seated in bearing
                    bores (.0015 approx.) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401524">Figure 24</hotlnk>). This is necessary for proper pinion position.
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401524" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1401524" filename="../figg14/G1401524.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 24. Feeler Gauge To Ensure Bearing Cups Are Seated</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install inner pinion oil seal into the carrier with the tabs locking into the oil
                    channel. Make sure the flat side of the seal is seated against the bottom of the bearing cup bore so
                    that the lip side will be against the pinion oil slinger.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install pinion into carrier. The pinion should be restrained from end movement by using
                    a retaining strap (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f1401525">Figure 25</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f1401525" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g1401525" filename="../figg14/G1401525.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="232px" resolution="72"/>
                    <caption>Figure 25. Retaining Strap on Pinion</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate carrier to a vertical position. Place selective preload spacer on pinion. Install
                    outer bearing cone onto pinion.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The reason for not assembling a new pinion oil seal at this time is due to the possibility
                            of having to adjust pinion preload or pinion position. It would be necessary to again remove
                            the seal and, as mentioned, whenever seals are removed, they are to be discarded because of
                            possible damage.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect end yoke seal surface for grooves caused by seal lip. If grooves can be detected
                    with a fingernail, yoke should be replaced.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Assemble end yoke, washer, and old pinion nut onto pinion. Tighten nut to: 700 to 900
                    ft-lbs. (949 to 1220 N&#8226;m). The old nut can be used during this adjustment phase of the
                    assembly, saving the new one for final assembly.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove pinion retainer strap. Using an in-lb. torque wrench, rotate pinion, noting
                    rolling torque. Rolling torque of pinion should read between 20 to 50 in-lbs. (2.3 to 5.7 N&#8226;m).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>To increase preload, decrease thickness of preload spacer; to decrease preload, increase
                            thickness of preload spacer. Every .001" (.025 mm) change in thickness of preload spacer
                            changes torque to rotate by approximately 30 in-lbs.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>A selective pinion bearing spacer is used to develop pinion bearing preload. The spacer is
                            available in the following thicknesses (
                            <hotlnk xrefid="t1401503">Spacer Thickness Chart</hotlnk>
